    "# Python Introduction for BA575 at Oregon State University"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Why Python?\n",
    "The practice of data science involves many interrelated but different activities, including accessing data, manipulating data, computing statistics about data, plotting/graphing/visualizing data, building predictive and explanatory models from data, evaluating those models on yet more data, integrating models into production systems, etc. Python is the programming language of choice for data scientists because it offers the power to do all of these things with relatively little overhead in terms of learning, installation or development time. \n",
    "\n",
    "Put simply, Python:\n",
    "* Reads like English – shallow learning curve\n",
    "* Used heavily in business analytics, science, …\n",
    "* Major Web development language\n",
    "* Expressive but very structured – whitespace sensitive!\n",
    "* In the workplace, Python powers a lot of Google and many other companies\n",
    "* The language itself is open source and so are many 3rd party libraries\n",
    "\n",
    "The [Official Python Tutorial](https://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/) is a great place to start getting a feel for the language. There are **many** other web sites and blogs with great tutorials and information about using Python for Business Analytics. Here are just a few of them:\n",
    "* [How to Think Like a Computer Scientist](http://interactivepython.org/runestone/static/thinkcspy/index.html)\n",
    "* [Dive Into Python](http://www.diveintopython.net/toc/index.html)\n",
    "* [Learn Python](http://www.learnpython.org)\n",
    "* [Learn Python the Hard Way](http://learnpythonthehardway.org)\n",
    "* [Practical Business Python](http://pbpython.com)\n",
    "* [Learning Python - suggestions and resources for business and analytics students and professionals](http://hselab.org/learning-python-suggestions-and-resources-for-business-analytics-students-and-professionals.html)\n",
    "* [Getting Started with Python for Data Scientists](http://www.datacommunitydc.org/blog/2013/03/getting-started-with-python-for-data-scientists/)\n",
    "* [Python for Data Scientists: The Landscape of Tutorials](http://www.datacommunitydc.org/blog/2013/07/python-for-data-analysis-the-landscape-of-tutorials/)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Which Python?\n",
    "\n",
    "There are two branches of current releases in Python: the older-syntax Python 2, and the newer-syntax Python 3. When it became clear that some non-backwards-compatible changes to the language were necessary, the Python dev-team decided to go through a transition during which the new language features would be introduced and the old language would still be actively maintained to make such a transition as easy as possible. The current \"end of life\" date for Python 2 is 2020, and it will soon be time to make the change to Python 3. However, the vast majority of the data science and analytics community still relies on tools written for Python 2.x. That is what we will use in BA575. We'll note any important differences between the two versions along the way.\n",
    "\n",
    "With this in mind, this introduction assumes you have a Python distribution that includes:\n",
    "\n",
    "* [Python](http://www.python.org) - version 2.7\n",
    "* [Matplotlib](http://matplotlib.sf.net) - excellent plotting and graphing libraries\n",
    "* [Jupyter Notebook](http://jupyter.org)\n",
    "\n",
    "A good, easy to install option that supports Mac, Windows, and Linux, and that has these packages (and much more) is the  [Continuum Anaconda](http://continuum.io/anaconda/) distribution package. We will assume that this is your Python environment in BA575. There are similar packages and other ways to configure Python for data analytics, but Anaconda provides the best overall way to get up and running quickly and easily. Best of all, it's **FREE.**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Jupyter Notebooks\n",
    "\n",
    "[Project Jupyter](http://jupyter.org) provides a rich architecture and environment for interactive computing, analysis, and sharing. [Jupyter Notebooks](https://jupyter.readthedocs.io/en/latest/content-quickstart.html) like this one provide browser-based support for data exploration and visualization (the focus of BA575) with Python code, text, mathematical expressions, inline plots and other rich media. These notebooks are normal files that can be shared with colleagues, converted to other formats such as HTML or PDF, etc. You can share any publicly available notebook by using the [Jupyter Notebook Viewer](http://nbviewer.jupyter.org) service which will render it as a static web page. This makes it easy to give your colleagues a document they can read immediately without having to install anything. \n",
    "\n",
    "Until recently, we used a slightly different version known as [IPython Notebook](http://ipython.readthedocs.io/en/stable/). You will often see references to IPython Notebooks. In fact, parts of BA575 may still reference them - sorry for the confusion! Jupyter can read IPython Notebooks, but Jupyter Notebooks are not backward compatible. When you open an IPython Notebook with Jupyter, it automatically converts (migrates) to the newer format. This makes it possible to continue to benefit from the large collection of available IPython Notebooks.\n",
    "\n",
    "Jupyter notebooks have become the *de facto* standard for presenting Python analyses. Entire books have now been written as Jupyter/IPython notebooks. Here are some interesting ones:\n",
    "   [A gallery of interesting IPython Notebooks](https://github.com/ipython/ipython/wiki/A-gallery-of-interesting-IPython-Notebooks)\n",
    "\n",
    "Jupyter notebooks provide easy way both to get important everyday work done as well as to communicate what was done, how it was done, and why it matters. We will use Jupyter notebooks extensively in BA575. \n",
    "\n",
    "This is a [nice tutorial](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HW29067qVWk&t=63s) on how to use the notebooks. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
