    "## Variables"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In our example, meal and tip_percent aren't literal numbers. They are variables. You can define variables using the equals (=) sign. \n",
    "\n",
    "In Python, variables are like buckets. You can put anything you want in them. Just give them a name and you can use them in place of the literal value.\n",
    "\n",
    "In our example, meal was 200.00 but we could also set meal to the text 'Hello, World'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "200.0\n",
      "Hello, World!\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "meal = 200.00\n",
    "print meal\n",
    "meal = \"Hello, World!\"\n",
    "print meal"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The value a variable has only depends on what it was last assigned.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here's another simple example:"
   ]
  },
