     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "2000 / 0"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Python tries to tell you where it stopped understanding. It also tries to show you where on the line the problem happened with caret (\"^\"). Finally it tells you the type of thing that went wrong, (NameError, SyntaxError, ZeroDivisionError) and a bit more information like \"name 'gibberish' is not defined\" or \"unexpected EOF while parsing\".\n",
    "Unfortunately you might not find \"unexpected EOF while parsing\" too helpful. EOF stands for End of File, but what file? What is parsing? Python does it's best, but it does take a bit of time to develop a knack for what these messages mean. If you run into an error you don't understand ask someone or search somewhere like Stack Overflow."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can name a variable *almost* anything you want. It needs to start with an alphabetical character or \"\\_\", can contain alphanumeric charcters plus underscores (\"\\_\"). Certain words, however, are reserved for the language:\n",
    "\n",
    "    and, as, assert, break, class, continue, def, del, elif, else, except, \n",
    "    exec, finally, for, from, global, if, import, in, is, lambda, not, or,\n",
    "    pass, print, raise, return, try, while, with, yield\n",
