   "source": [
    "##Formatting\n",
    "\n",
    "We have used very simple print statements with no special formatting in this tutorial:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 130,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Hello\n",
      "Evan Smouse\n",
      "Hello, Evan Smouse\n",
      "Hello, World!\n",
      "This is a longer statement.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print 'Hello'\n",
    "my_name = 'Evan Smouse'\n",
    "print my_name\n",
    "print 'Hello,', my_name\n",
    "statement = 'Hello, ' + 'World!'\n",
    "print statement\n",
    "print \"This \" + \"is \" + \"a \" + \"longer \" + \"statement.\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A common way to format output is to use \"C-style\" string formatting to create new, formatted strings. The \"%\" operator is used to format a set of variables enclosed in a tuple, together with a format string, which contains normal text together with \"argument specifiers\", special symbols like \"%s\" and \"%d\".\n",
    "\n",
    "Here is an example:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 131,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Hello, John!\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "name = \"John\"\n",
    "print \"Hello, %s!\" % name"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "... and ..."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 132,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "John is 23 years old.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "name = \"John\"\n",
    "age = 23\n",
    "print \"%s is %d years old.\" % (name, age)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This style of formatting has been around for a **LONG** time and is understood by most programmers.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here are the basics:\n",
    "\n",
    "    %s - String (or any object with a string representation, like numbers)\n",
    "    %d - Integers\n",
    "    %f - Floating point numbers\n",
    "    %.<number of digits>f - Floating point numbers with a fixed amount of digits to the right of the dot.\n",
    "    %x/%X - Integers in hex representation (lowercase/uppercase)\n",
    "\n",
    "For a good overview, look [here](http://www.learnpython.org/en/String_Formatting).\n",
    "\n",
    "This style works well for relatively simple output:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 133,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      " pi = 3.14 \n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pi = 3.14159\n",
    "print(\" pi = %1.2f \" % pi)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 134,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      " cats and dogs living together\n",
      " cats and dogs living together\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "s1 = \"cats\"\n",
    "s2 = \"dogs\"\n",
    "print \" %s and %s living together\" % (s1, s2)\n",
    "s3 = \" %s and %s living together\" % (s1, s2)\n",
    "print s3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
