   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A newer way to format strings was introduced in Python 2.6, and it is becoming much more common. It will also be found in Python 3.\n",
    "\n",
    "With the new python string formatter, you can use numbered parameters so you don’t have to count how many you have, at least on half of it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 136,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "' (3, 5, 12.4, -11.2, 5, 131, 53, -91.34) '"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 136,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "set = \" ({0}, {1}, {2}, {3}, {4}, {5}, {6}, {7}) \".format(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h)\n",
    "set"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The new string formatter is different from lower and upper because it can take other arguments. An *argument* is what coders call the value passed to an operation or function, it doesn't mean we are fighting. A simple introduction is [here](https://mkaz.com/2012/10/10/python-string-format/)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 137,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "' I took the cheese off the table '"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 137,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "madlib = \" I {verb} the {object} off the {place} \".format(verb=\"took\", object=\"cheese\", place=\"table\")\n",
    "madlib"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 138,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Hello, Evan Smouse!\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "my_name = \"Evan Smouse\"\n",
    "string = \"Hello, {0}!\"\n",
    "print(string.format(my_name))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can also used literal strings:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 139,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Hello, Evan Smouse!\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Hello, {0}!\".format(\"Evan Smouse\"))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "{0} is where the first argument, \"Evan Smouse\", to format() is placed in the resulting text. \n",
    "\n",
    "{1} would mean use the second value if there was one:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 140,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "'Evan Smouse likes Python'"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 140,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "\"{0} likes {1}\".format(\"Evan Smouse\", 'Python')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##Line Endings\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's say we want to represent a string in one string variable that prints this:\n",
    "\n",
    "    Oregon State University\n",
    "    Corvallis, OR\n",
    "\n",
    "A line ending is one example of something which is part of text on the screen that we need to somehow represent in a string. The key is the backslash (\"\\\") character. \"\\n\" and \"\\r\\n\" represent two kinds of line endings. You can learn more on Stack Overflow.\n",
    "\n",
    "Try adding \"\\n\" in the right place in the next cell to make it appear like the address text in this cell."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 143,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Oregon State University\n",
      "Corvallis, OR\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Oregon State University\\nCorvallis, OR\")"
   ]
  },
  {
